comments.text:
The HTML5 spec says that:

When an audio element is not exposing a user interface, the user agent is expected to hide it, irrespective of CSS rules.

http://www.w3.org/Bugs/Public/show_bug.cgi?id=12881 proposes making this a little more explicit, but either way the intent is clear -- this rule in html.css:

audio:not([controls]) {
  display: none;
}

should be !important so that authors can't override it.

(That said, it should *also* be restricted to elements that have script enabled, given http://dev.w3.org/html5/spec/the-iframe-element.html#user-interface .  In other words, HTML5 says that when script is disabled the controls-attribute behavior should happen implicitly.  I suppose we need a pseudo-class for whether script is enabled to do that.)

